<HEAD>Kennedy Supports Increasing Minimum Wage To $5.05 Per Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of
the Senate Labor and Resources Committee, expressed his support
Friday for increasing the minimum wage to $5.05 per hour over four
years but said he still remains committed to raises tied to
inflation.
   ``I continue to support indexing,'' said Kennedy, in a statement
released by his Washington office. ``It's the best way to make the
minimum wage a living wage.''
   Kennedy said his committee has scheduled action on the minimum
wage bill during the week of April 11.
   The House Education and Labor Committee voted Thursday to raise
the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour in several steps over the
next four years.
   The vote to increase the minimum wage to $5.05, instead of the
$4.65 voted last week by the House labor standards subcommittee,
was seen as an attempt by supporters of an increase to gain a
bargaining chip that will assure the minimum wage will be at least
$4.65 when the measure leaves the House.
   Last week, the subcommittee approved a bill to raise the
$3.35-an-hour minimum wage to $3.85 in 1989, $4.25 in 1990 and
$4.65 in 1991. At the same time, the subcommittee voted to strip
the bill of a controversial proposal that would have indexed or
tied future increases to the rate of inflation.
   ``A fourth year increase is less satisfactory, but it could make
a stronger package, given the president's veto threats,'' said
Kennedy. ``The last time Congress raised the minimum wage in 1977,
we enacted a four-step increase, too.''
</TEXT>
