<HEAD>Kennedy Scales Back Proposal To Increase Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to correct amount of increase proposed by
Quayle</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy unveiled a scaled-down
proposal Wednesday to increase the federal minimum wage $1.20 to
$4.55 an hour over the next three years.
   The labor-supported proposal from the Massachusetts Democrat
came as the Senate Labor Committee began deliberations on Kennedy's
earlier minimum wage bill. Republican Sens. Strom Thurmond of South
Carolina and Dan Quayle of Indiana immediately expressed their
opposition.
   Kennedy's original bill would have boosted the minimum wage, now
at $3.35 per hour, by 50 cents next year, 40 cents in 1990 and 40
cents in 1991, with automatic increases tied to inflation to keep
it at 50 percent of the average wage nationally.
   The House Labor Committee already has completed action on a
measure that would raise the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour
over the next four years. It is understood, however, that the House
panel's chairman, Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., will offer
the Kennedy proposal as a substitute when the measure gets to the
House floor sometime after the July 4 recess.
   In its brief meeting Wednesday, the Senate Labor Committee
rejected 12-4 an amendment by Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who wanted
Puerto Rico to be required to keep the federal minimum wage.
   Kennedy's proposal includes Puerto Rico, but permits the country
to exempt itself if the island's minimum wage board certifies to
the labor secretary that there is a ``substantial finding of
unemployment.''
   In introducing his substitute bill, Kennedy said the current
minimum wage has fallen to its lowest point since its inception 50
years ago, with today's minimum of $3.35 per hour representing only
36 percent of the average hourly earnings.
   Historically, he said, the minimum has been maintained at a
figure of one-half the hourly average.
   ``Congressional action to restore the minimum wage is long
overdue,'' he said.
   Thurmond said, however, said he was opposed to a significant
increase in the minimum wage because ``it is inflationary, it
reduces entry-level and part-time jobs for teen-agers and unskilled
workers, as well as decreases services to consumers.''
   He said only ``big labor'' would benefit from an increased
minimum wage.
   ``Minimum wage legislation has always been promoted by labor
unions and other special interest groups for their purely
self-serving political considerations,'' Thurmond said. ``The labor
unions in our country are looking to this measure as a means of
securing their positions and turning around a decline in membership
that they have experienced in recent years.''
   Quayle said he would propose an amendment which would increase
the minimum wage to $4 and combine it with a reform of the earned
income tax credit, similar to an approach presented in the House
Labor Committee by Rep. Tom Petri, R-Wis., but rejected by the
panel.
</TEXT>
