<HEAD>Committee Approves Minimum Wage Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moves by Congress to raise the federal minimum
wage this year will put presidential candidates on the spot and
force them to take a position on the issue, the chairman of the
House labor committee says.
   ``They like to say they are for a good education or a living
wage for everyone,'' said Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins. ``They will
have to discuss in detail the numbers that Congress sets. They
won't be able to just say they are for a living wage.''
   The House Labor and Education Committee on Wednesday ignored the
threat of a presidential veto and approved legislation to raise the
minimum wage from $3.35 per hour to $5.05 over the next four years.
   The measure, which passed after numerous Republican attempts to
weaken or gut it, now goes to the full House.
   ``This will be one of the great election issues,'' Hawkins,
D-Calif., said in an interview. ``Each candidate will be pinned
down.''
   The Democratic-controlled committee approved the measure by
voice vote after rejecting a Republican proposal to permit a
special ``new hire'' wage of $3.35 an hour.
   Hawkins said he expected the full House to take up the
legislation within 10 days after members return April 11 from their
Easter recess.
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee will take up a
similar bill during the week of April 11, according to its
chairman, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin says senior White House advisers
will urge President Reagan to veto any minimum wage increase that
would lead to a decrease in the number of job opportunities.
   The initial House bill would have raised the minimum to $4.65 an
hour over three years; that figure is still contained in the Senate
bill. The administration claims the proposal would result in
elimination of 880,000 jobs because employers won't be willing to
pay their workers that much.
   Under the House committee-passed bill, the minimum wage would go
to $3.85 an hour next year, $4.25 in 1990, $4.65 in 1991 and $5.05
in 1992.
   Last week, the committee added the fourth-year increase of 40
cents as a substitute for ``indexing'' _ or tying _ future raises
to inflation.
   Indexing was supported by Hawkins, Kennedy and organized labor,
but Democrats dropped the plan because they feared it would result
in little or no increase this year.
   The final version of the bill was sent to the House floor after
the committee defeated, 20-13, a proposal by Rep. Steve Bartlett,
R-Texas, to create a ``new hire'' or training wage by which
employers could pay new workers $3.35 an hour for 90 days.
   Bartlett said the White House told him the president would veto
any legislation not containing a lower starting wage.
   Rep. Matthew G. Martinez, D-Calif., called the training wage
proposal ``a sham, a joke and a fraud.'' He said it was ``nothing
more than a way to get around the minimum wage.''
   The committee also rejected another Bartlett amendment which
would have given private employers the right to grant compensatory
time off in lieu of wages for overtime.
   Also defeated by a voice vote was an amendment by Rep. Thomas E.
Petri, R-Wis., to permit employers to include the cost of fringe
benefits, such as health insurance, in the calculation of the
minimum wage and an amendment by Rep. William F. Goodling, R-Pa.,
to exempt motorcycle dealers from paying overtime.
   Robert McGlotten, legislative director of the AFL-CIO, said the
committee ``recognized the need to bring this nation's working poor
to at least the poverty level by gradually raising the minimum
wage.''
</TEXT>
