<HEAD>House Democrat Offers Alternative Minimum Wage Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Democrat has proposed raising the
minimum wage to $4.25 by next year, but his attempt at breaking an
impasse between Congress and President Bush contains provisions the
White House has insisted it won't accept.
   Rep. Austin J. Murphy, D-Pa., introduced a revised minimum-wage
bill Wednesday, a week after Bush vetoed legislation that would have
raised the wage from $3.35 an hour to $4.55 by 1991.
   The House last week was unable to override the veto, Bush's first.
   Murphy, chairman of the House subcommittee with jurisdiction over
the minimum wage, proposed raising the hourly minimum wage to $3.80
on Oct. 1 and to $4.25 a year later.
   His final target matches that of Bush, although the minimum wage
would not reach $4.25 an hour until January 1992 under the
president's proposal.
   Murphy's proposal gave no ground on the issue on which the
majority Democrats in Congress and Bush have their greatest
difference _ whether employers should be allowed to pay newly hired
workers a subminimum wage for an initial training period.
   Bush has said he will not support any increase in the minimum
wage unless Congress also establishes a new subminimum wage
employers could pay all new workers for up to six months.
   Democrats intially resisted any attempts to establish a
subminimum wage, but eventually included in the measure Bush vetoed
a provision allowing the lower wage to be paid to workers with fewer
than 60 days' work experience.
   Murphy included the same 60-day provision in his bill.
   ``I reject the president's call for a six-month training wage,
mainly because it is excessive and unfair,'' Murphy said in a
statement.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., has re-introduced legislation in
the Senate identical to the measure Bush vetoed, but has indicated a
willingness to discuss a compromise with the White House.
   Administration officials have said Bush's proposal is the only
acceptable one.
</TEXT>
