<HEAD>White House, Senate Democrats to Heat up Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats and the White House will
clash directly for the first time next week over raising the $3.35
hourly minimum wage, with more skirmishes expected before the
nation's 5 million lowest paid workers get an increase.
   Leaders of both parties in the Senate agreed Friday to hold
back-to-back votes Tuesday _ the first on the latest Democratic
version for annual increases of 40 cents an hour to $4.55 by
October 1991, and the second on Bush's offer of yearly 30-cent
boosts to $4.25 by January 1992.
   Republican Leader Bob Dole conceded his party and Bush are
likely to lose both votes. But Dole expressed confidence of a
victory when the president vetoes the measure, as he promised again
Friday, and Democrats attempt to override the veto.
   The chief sponsor of the raise, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
acknowledged he lacks the 16 additional votes needed to muster a
two-thirds majority for overriding a presidential veto.
   ``I would hope they don't again lay down this line in the
sand,'' Kennedy said, challenging the administration's insistence
on no more compromises. ``They've come a long way, we've come a
long way.''
   Democrats on Friday subtracted a dime from the $4.65 federal
floor on wages they had wanted, and they accepted for the first
time a 60-day subminimum ``training wage'' for workers entering
their first job.
   Bush, however, told reporters he had ``no intention of budging
one inch'' on allowing a minimum wage that high or on accepting
that short a period during which employers could pay a ``training
wage'' 20 percent below the federal floor.
   ``I will veto any bill which exceeds a $4.25 wage level and
which does not contain a six-month training wage for new hires,''
he said in a letter Friday to Dole.
   The latest Democratic plan was put together by Kennedy and Sens.
Bob Graham of Florida and David Pryor of Arkansas. Except for minor
differences on the subminimum scale, it is identical to a bill
passed by the House last month.
   In the House version, an employer could pay the lower subminimum
skill only to workers in their first job. The Senate measure would
require a worker to have at least 60 days' experience in one or
more jobs before any employer would have to pay the higher scale.
   Bush's subminimum would allow employers to continue paying $3.35
to any new hires, regardless of their previous experience, for six
months. That subminimum would rise to $3.40 an hour in 1992 under
the president's proposal while the Democrats would do away with it
entirely then.
</TEXT>
