<HEAD>House Seeks Compromise on Minimum Wage Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans and conservative Democrats who
sustained President Bush's veto of an increase in the minimum wage
are pushing the White House to compromise on a scaled-back version
of the bill.
   Administration officials, however, are sending mixed signals,
floating possible concessions one day but insisting the next that
Bush won't budge from last spring's ``best, first and only offer.''
   Compromise or not, House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., said Thursday that a bill raising the wage floor to $4.25
from the $3.35 level where it's been since 1981 will be voted on
Wednesday.
   Bush vetoed a bill in June that would have increased the minimum
wage to $4.55 an hour and established a subminimum training wage of
$3.35 for the first 60 days of a first-time worker's employment.
   He vowed to do the same again on any subsequent attempt that
goes higher than $4.25 an hour, hits that level before 1992 or
provides for less than a six-month subminimum scale for any new
hires, regardless of previous job experience.
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu told House Speaker Thomas
S. Foley, D-Wash., and GOP leader Robert H. Michel of Illinois on
Thursday that Bush wouldn't budge.
   ``We didn't reach agreement on anything,'' Foley told reporters
after the White House meeting.
   Michel held out hope ``there may be room for some bending.''
   ``The president will have to bend a little bit'' to avoid a veto
fight, he said. ``I don't think the president would enjoy vetoing a
second minimum wage bill.''
   Senate Republicans, led by Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas
and Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, also have been urging the
White House to compromise.
   However, lawmakers and lobbyists on both sides said the White
House didn't begin focusing on the issue until late last week and
is scrambling for a way to prevent its allies from jumping to the
other side.
   ``They want to come in at the last minute and make a deal, but
there's no firm decision on what they want,'' said Rep. Timothy J.
Penny of Minnesota, one of 28 Democrats who voted last summer to
sustain Bush's veto.
   Sununu, according to congressional sources and lobbyists,
earlier this week floated as a possible compromise gradually
increasing the wage floor to $4.25 an hour by July 1991 _ six
months earlier than Bush wanted _ with a three-month subminimum for
new hires. But it was not put forth Thursday.
   ``They're floundering all over the place,'' said Robert
McGlotten, the AFL-CIO's chief lobbyist. ``They keep talking like
they want to make some movement. But when we sit down with them, we
get nowhere.''
   A strategist for a business group opposed to any increase
agreed. Speaking on the condition of anonymity, he said
administration officials this week presented one possible training
wage compromise ``that was so convoluted and complicated that it
could never be used.''
   McGlotten said ``there's no give'' by unions on the issue of
achieving a 90-cent increase to $4.25 an hour by January 1991, but
he expressed a willingness to negotiate the training wage issue as
long as employers are prevented from using it as a perpetual source
of below minimum-scale labor.
   Whatever the outcome, liberal Democrats and supporters of Bush's
earlier veto agree that minimum wage supporters have the upper hand.
   Democrats want to have a bill approved by both the House and
Senate and on Bush's desk before the Nov. 13 arrival in Washington
of Polish Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, believing his visit will
make a veto more difficult.
   ``There is a lot of nervousness on the part of the White House
that they could look like a mean old ogre, fighting day and night
to get a capital gains tax break while also fighting equally hard
against raising the minimum wage,'' Penny said.
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said supporters still lack a
two-thirds, veto-proof majority for the new bill, which would raise
the wage floor to $3.80 in January and to $4.25 by January 1991
with a 60-day training wage only for first-time workers.
   ``But we're gaining ground,'' Bonior said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

