after the White House meeting.
   Bush, in what he called a ``best and only offer,'' promised
shortly after taking office to veto any bill that would raise the
minimum wage above $4.25 an hour or that reached that level before
Jan. 1, 1992.
   Coupled with any increase, he said, must be a six-month
subminimum training wage that would maintain the current wage floor
of $3.35 an hour for newly hired workers, regardless of their
experience.
