<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Labor Committee approved a bill that would boost the minimum wage to $5.05 an hour over the next four years. 

   The committee backed the measure by a voice vote, after rejecting several Republican-sponsored amendments aimed at weakening the effect of the increases, or otherwise giving employers a wage-cost break. 

   Under the legislation, the hourly minimum wage, which has stood at $3.35 since 1981, would rise to $3.85 next year, $4.25 in 1990, $4.65 in 1991, and $5.05 in 1992. 
A bill to raise the wage floor also is pending in the Senate. 

   Robert McGlotten, the AFL-CIO legislative director, said the committee "recognized the need to bring this nation's 'working poor' to at least the poverty level by gradually raising the minimum wage." 

   But Robert Martin, human resources manager for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said a study the Chamber sponsored shows that the first three years of increases alone would cost 550,000 jobs at companies that cannot afford the higher wage, and the additional, fourth-year rise "adds insult to injury." 

   "I kind of shudder at what the reaction of the small-business community will be," he added. 

   The bill is expected to be considered by the full House next month. 
The measure before the Senate Labor Committee would raise the hourly minimum to $4.65 after three years, and after that, tie the wage floor to the average wage paid to manufacturing workers nationwide. 

   The House bill was amended last week by a Labor subcommittee, which killed the manufacturing-wage indexing provision and, partly in compensation, added the increase to $5.05 an hour in the fourth year. 

   The minimum wage legislation is an important part of a legislative push by unions and other employee groups to improve workers' pay, benefits and working conditions; many of the measures had been stalled in Congress through most of the years of the Reagan administration. 
The administration opposes the wage floor bill, but didn't take an active role in fighting the House committee action. 

   The proposed amendments turned aside yesterday by the House committee were rejected mostly along party lines. 
An amendment offered by Steve Bartlett (R., Texas) would have kept the minimum wage at $3.35 an hour for the first 90 days of work by newly hired employees; it was rejected, 20-13. 

   That "for-hire" provision was a version of other plans for keeping the minimum wage low for workers with the least experience. 
Administration and other critics of wage-floor increases say such a low wage is necessary to encourage employers to take on new, untrained workers. 
The idea had been called a "youth subminimum wage" but, more recently, its backers have used terms like "youth opportunity wage" or "training wage." 

   Other amendments, rejected by voice votes, would have: expanded an existing option for employers to give certain workers compensatory time off for working overtime, rather than requiring them to pay employees at 1.5 times their basic wage; included fringe benefits in calculating payment of the minimum wage; and exempted motorcycle dealers from the wage floor. 

</TEXT>
